# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- `contracts/FSushiBill.sol`, `contracts/FSushiCookV0.sol`, `contracts/SousChef.sol`, `contracts/FSushiKitchen.sol`, `contracts/FlashStrategySushiSwap.sol`: reward distribution, checkpointing, and principal/accounting flow integrity
- `contracts/FarmingLPToken.sol`: share mint/burn, reward-debt accounting, withdrawal/exit-path consistency, LP valuation sensitivity
- `contracts/FSushiBar.sol`, `contracts/libraries/FSushiBarPriorityQueue.sol`: lock/share bookkeeping and timestamp-based queue snapshot integrity
- `contracts/FSushiAirdropsVotingEscrow.sol`, `contracts/libraries/Snapshots.sol`: historical state reconstruction, checkpoint lookup, and claim accounting
- `contracts/FSushiAirdrops.sol`, `contracts/FlashStrategySushiSwapFactory.sol`, `contracts/base/BaseERC20.sol`: touched as edge-case / sanity-check surfaces, but still comparatively underexplored

## Issue Directions Seen
- Reward-accounting corruption around checkpoint timing, backdated accrual, and duplicated entitlement paths
- Share/reward-debt desynchronization in LP staking flows, especially across deposit, withdrawal, emergency/exit, and fee/precision edges
- Locking/bar accounting inconsistencies where shares, queued deposits, and unlock state can diverge
- Historical snapshot/checkpoint logic as a recurring weakness, including same-timestamp overwrite behavior and broken past-state reconstruction
- Flash-strategy accounting risk centered on principal tracking versus realized balances or rewards
- Arithmetic and initialization edge cases recur, but the stronger patterns so far are accounting-state mismatches rather than isolated math faults

## Useful Context
- Highest sustained attention has clustered around `FSushiBar*`, `FarmingLPToken`, `FSushiBill`, and `FSushiAirdropsVotingEscrow`
- Cross-agent overlap most clearly reinforced the `FSushiBarPriorityQueue` same-timestamp overwrite pattern
- Retained findings so far concentrate in four durable clusters: bill/reward accounting, fLP accounting and exits, bar lock bookkeeping, and ve-airdrop historical claims
- The broader codebase pattern is state derived from historical checkpoints or queued snapshots being fragile when multiple actions compress into the same accounting boundary

